{{other uses|Assembly hall (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Braintree hill meeting house.jpg|right|thumb|200px|A Vermont meeting hall, from [[Braintree, Vermont|Braintree]], [[Vermont]], USA.]]
An '''assembly hall''' is a kind of [[Hall|function hall]], a large room used to hold public meetings or meetings of the members of an organization such as a school, church, or [[deliberative assembly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/assembly-hall|title=Assembly hall definition and meaning - Collins English Dictionary|author=|date=|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> An example of the last case is the [[Assembly Hall (Washington, Mississippi)]] where the general assembly of the state of [[Mississippi]] was held. Some [[Christian]] denominations call their meeting places or places of worship assembly halls, for example the [[Salt Lake Assembly Hall]]. Elders and ministers of [[Presbyterian]] churches gather in assembly halls for their [[General Assembly (Presbyterian church)|general assembly]], such as in the [[General Assembly Hall of the Church of Scotland]].
==Function hall== [[File:Royal_Palace_Banquet_Hall.jpg|left|thumb|Banquet hall and [[wedding reception]] venue]] A '''function hall''', '''reception hall''', or '''banquet hall''' is a room or building for the purpose of hosting a [[party]], [[banquet]], [[Wedding reception|wedding]] or other reception, or other social event. Function halls are often found within [[pub]]s, [[Nightclub|club]]s, [[hotel]]s, or [[restaurant]]s. Some are run by [[fraternal organizations]] and rented out as part of them being a club, for example [[Masonic Temple|Masonic Halls]]. The first recorded mention of "function rooms" is in 1922. <ref>{{cite journal|author1=National Electrical Contractors Association|title=Electrical Construction and Maintenance|journal=Electrical Construction and Maintenance|date=1922|volume=22|page=58|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_Hw3AQAAMAAJ&q=%22function+rooms%22&dq=%22function+rooms%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A0_JVOr1LIGqU4r-gCg&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA|accessdate=28 January 2015|publisher=McGraw-Hill Publishing Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ngram Viewer|url=https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=function+rooms%2Cfunction+room%2Cfunction+hall%2Cfunction+halls&year_start=1800&year_end=2000&corpus=15&smoothing=3&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2Cfunction%20rooms%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cfunction%20room%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cfunction%20hall%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cfunction%20halls%3B%2Cc0|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref>
==Gallery== <center> <gallery widths=175> Image:The_Mira_Hong_Kong_3rd-floor-Function-Rooms_Enterance.jpg|Nightclub Function Room. Image:Function_Rooms_Melbourne.jpg|Function Room in Melbourne Image:Chinese banquet in a banquet hall.JPG|Chinese banquet hall Image:Function Room Brisbane.jpg|Brisbane Hire Venue Image:Function Halls Across India.jpg|Function Halls Across India </gallery> </center>
==College and university campuses== {{See also|Arena|List of indoor arenas in the United States #Major college indoor arenas}} On the campuses of [[college]]s and [[universities]] in the United States, assembly halls are sometimes found in multi-purpose athletic buildings, where they share other uses, including as [[basketball court]]s. Examples are [[Assembly Hall (Bloomington)]] and (formerly) [[Assembly Hall (Champaign)]].
