{{Infobox recurring event |name = National Bikers Roundup |native_name = |logo = [[File:National Bikers Roundup logo.png]] |logo_caption = |image = |imagesize = |caption = |date = August |begins = |ends = |frequency = Annual |location = Kansas City, Missouri |years_active = 39<!--{{age|YYYY|mm|dd}} Date of the first occurrence--> |first = 1977 |last = |genre = [[Motorcycle rally]] |budget = |participants = 30,000–40,000 |patron = Dallas Thibodeaux & Rozell Nunn, jnr |website = {{url|www.nationalbikersroundup.org}} |footnotes = }}
The '''National Bikers Roundup''' is the largest [[camping]] [[motorcycle rally]] in the USA and is organized by a group of [[African American]] [[motorcycle clubs]]. Its location changes every year<ref>American Motorcyclist Jul 1995</ref> but every decade it returns to its founding city of [[Kansas City, Missouri]]. More than 1,000 motorcycle clubs attend the event and black women make up close to half of participants.<ref name=Samuels2007>{{Citation |title=Black Bikers: the rides and the history |first=Adrienne P |last=Samuels |magazine= [[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |location= Chicago |date= October 2007 |volume=62 |issue= 12 |pages= 98&ndash;106 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cdMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA98 |accessdate=2010-02-04}}</ref>
==History== First organized in 1977 by Dallas Thibodeaux and Rozell Nunn, Jnr attracting 49 riders, it has since grown to a five-day event, with up to 30,000 participants, who enjoy camping, exhibition, parades, stunt shows, entertainment and a host of other motorcycle-related experiences including drag racing and a "biggest gut contest".<ref name="ebony">Black Bikers:the rides and the history. Samuels, Adrienne P. Samuels. Ebony, Volumes 62-63, Johnson Pub. Company Oct 2007</ref><ref>[http://www.nbrkcmo.com/ Official website]</ref>
The event serves to unite the Black motorcycle community and promote camaraderie. Starting from 1998, each year participants donate food and money to support local food paid programmes. By 2000, donations had reached 16,000 tonnes and $9,000.<ref>A Gathering of Friends. Kresnak, Bill. American Motorcyclist, Dec 2001</ref>
Due to the history of [[racism|racial segregation]] in the USA, the event was largely ignored by the media and motorcycle industry for most of its history but is now supported by manufacturers such as [[Honda]] and [[Harley-Davidson]], which was the first major company to attend,<ref name="ebony" /> and is both family friendly and open to all ethnicities.<ref>Road Signs, American Motorcyclist Jul 2001 P. 65</ref>
==Media coverage== The ''[[Tulsa World]]'' featured coverage of the 2014 Rally in Tulsa, Oklahoma, held July 30 to August 3.<ref>{{citation|title=National Bikers Roundup revvs up the fun in Tulsa|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/local/national-bikers-roundup-revvs-up-the-fun-in-tulsa/article_a4d87c0c-35ac-5bad-8981-7ce43d388644.html/|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref>
